snippet.textDisplay:
As I was born in South Carolina, the civil war was taught to my class almost every year in elementary school. The way they presented the civil war to us was rather interesting to say the least. While we were still taught that slavery was a bad thing, and that the south was ultimately wrong, the north was always portrayed as more corrupt and harsh then I think they really were. (Or maybe not, give me a break, I was 9 when I learned most of this.)

One of my teachers always called Sherman, "The man who scorched the south." What he did was seen as unnecessary and cruel, but very clever, and my teachers always said that what he did was "total warfare", which was how I was introduced to the term. If you ever take any kind of history tours in Georgia or South Carolina, you can visit some of the places he burned down. It's pretty interesting that he was taught about more than Lee was, just because of how efficient his tactics were, and because of how much damage he caused the state.

Another thing that I was taught, (not by all teachers, but a few), was how the war was about northern aggression. How the north was meddling in affairs they had no business in, and that they were the ones pushing the south into action. The south did depend very heavily on slaves, and by meddling with them, the south saw it as the north trying to cripple the south.

Interestingly, slavery for the north was always taught to us like this. The north really didn't give two shits about black people, even if they didn't like slavery. Slaves were used more like chess pieces than people. After all, if you freed the slaves, you took away the means of production and business from the south, ultimately crippling it. You could then gather those newly freed slaves, and use them to bring more numbers into your army, thus gaining more men, thus gaining more strength. Its actually very interesting when you look at it from that perspective.

When slavery was mentioned in class, that huge slave uprising was always pointed towards as one of the major upsets of how the way slaves were treated. I honestly don't know if what I'm saying is true or bs that is taught down here, but it was said that before the revolt, slaves weren't treated as, and I would like to repeat, AS cruelly. After the revolt, slave owners were terrified by the thought of their slaves rising up against them, (compare the amount of slaves on a major farm against the small amount of people who owned them, and you can understand why), and they started to hand out barbaric punishments to any slaves who even looked at them funny.

Fort Sumter is also very interesting. It's a weird thing to be taught about it because on one hand, HOLY SHIT SOUTH CAROLINA WAS BALLSY AS FUCK AND WE WERE THE ONES WHO LEFT FIRST AND WE'RE SO BADASS, THATS AWESOME, but....on the other hand, we were on the pro slavery side and that's so uncool. Shame South Carolina. Shame.

Abraham Lincoln on the other hand, WAS ALWAYS TAUGHT TO BE ONE OF THE MOST FUCKING BADASS DUDES EVER! No hate on the dude at all. His reconstruction plan was always looked at as more than generous, and I think I was taught even the south was shocked and devastated by his assassination. (Again, if this was wrong, it has been awhile since i studied the civil war closely.)

Reconstruction is ultimately whn I was taught that the north were nothing more than money hungry, no good carpet bagger yankee's who need to stay up north. (NOT WHAT I BELIEVE, DON'T HURT ME!!)

State pride is still very strong down here. I love my state, even if it's history is one huge black mark against it. To be fair, South Carolina has changed a lot from the civil wars times, and I would like to say that we've learned to walk away from racism for the most part. It makes me sad that all we're ever known for is starting one of the worst wars in U.S history and everyone still sees us a bunch of racist and uneducated hicks.

snippet.textDisplay: I’m a little disappointed in this series of videos. usually oversimplified does a decent job of giving an overall picture of the causes of a conflict like they did with the American revolution series. However many of the causes of the civil war had nothing to do with slavery and are problems that live on to this day. While I don’t want to understate the impact of slavery on the cause of the war I feel they fell into the trap so many others do of putting to much focus on it. The other causes of the war can help us understand today’s modern political problems and regional differences. If we understand and analyze what happened then it may help us understand one another and come to better compromises today. I feel with oversimplifieds entertaining ability to teach history, the overemphasizing of slavery as the cause instead of a more rounded look at the various causes was a missed opportunity.

snippet.textDisplay: Things to remember. The north kept slaves until the end of the war. Also, no casualties happened at Ft. Sumptner. Lincoln ordered the blockade before the war started. They were afraid to put Davis on trial, because most people believed Lincoln started the war unlawfully. That being said, I'm glad the union was preserved, and our great nation was preserved. I just don't like the precedent that was set, that if the government feels like changing its mind about the bill of rights, it can do so whenever it feels like under perceived "emergency situations". Like holding political enemies with out trial, or arresting Justices, and arresting journalist, or shutting down printing presses. Stuff like that.
